<i>... raising almost $200
for that year's telethon.</i>

228
00:14:59,493 --> 00:15:01,358
All of you send in
a bit of your allowance.

229
00:15:01,561 --> 00:15:04,689
Just a little bit.
A dime, a nickel, a penny.

230
00:15:04,898 --> 00:15:07,423
Every bit helps.

231
00:15:08,335 --> 00:15:10,496
<i>The goal of the telethon that year...</i>

232
00:15:10,704 --> 00:15:15,004
<i>... was $3.9 million, which was
a lot of dough at that time.</i>

233
00:15:15,208 --> 00:15:18,974
Thank you, Tom.
You're a prince among men.

234
00:15:19,179 --> 00:15:21,670
Whoa, Lanny. There are
children watching!

235
00:15:21,882 --> 00:15:23,372
Where does he get his energy?

236
00:15:23,884 --> 00:15:25,351
<i>To remind viewers of the goal...</i>

237
00:15:25,552 --> 00:15:29,648
<i>... we agreed the telethon
could run 39 hours nonstop.</i>

238
00:15:30,724 --> 00:15:34,820
<i>The show would begin at 9 p.m. On
Friday and finish at noon on Sunday.</i>

239
00:15:35,028 --> 00:15:37,360
<i>We paced it so that
Vince and I were together...</i>

240
00:15:37,564 --> 00:15:39,657
<i>... for the kickoff,
most of the day Saturday...</i>

241
00:15:39,866 --> 00:15:43,358
<i>... then the big finale
on Sunday with us bleary-eyed...</i>

242
00:15:43,570 --> 00:15:46,505
<i>... and weeping as America
got ready to go to church.</i>

243
00:15:46,706 --> 00:15:50,073
Lanny, Lanny. What are you doing?

244
00:15:50,277 --> 00:15:52,643
I'm ordering a pizza. I'm starving.

245
00:15:52,846 --> 00:15:56,577
No anchovies on mine, Lanny.
Hey, so who are you talking to?

246
00:15:56,783 --> 00:15:59,946
I'm talking to little Suzie
from Whittier, California...

247
00:16:00,153 --> 00:16:03,645
...and she is going to donate
three weeks of allowance.

248
00:16:03,857 --> 00:16:07,020
- How about that, folks?
- Suzie from Whittier, thank you.

249
00:16:07,227 --> 00:16:08,717
Three weeks of allowance.

250
00:16:08,929 --> 00:16:10,328
That's a challenge for all you...

251
00:16:10,530 --> 00:16:12,760
<i>What you have to understand
is that Vince and me...</i>

252
00:16:12,966 --> 00:16:15,127
<i>... were essentially a boy-girl act.</i>

253
00:16:15,335 --> 00:16:17,895
<i>I was the tramp,
ready for any sort of action...</i>

254
00:16:18,138 --> 00:16:19,696
<i>... and Vince was the gentleman...</i>

255
00:16:19,906 --> 00:16:22,033
<i>... always trying to make me
behave myself.</i>

256
00:16:22,242 --> 00:16:24,733
<i>I was pleasure, and he was control.</i>

257
00:16:25,078 --> 00:16:28,138
<i>I was rock 'n' roll,
and he was class.</i>

258
00:16:28,348 --> 00:16:32,682
<i>His presence gave America
permission to like me.</i>

259
00:16:35,122 --> 00:16:38,148
<i>My deal with the publisher
gave me first-class travel...</i>

260
00:16:38,358 --> 00:16:39,882
<i>... a luxury I'd never enjoyed.</i>

261
00:16:40,093 --> 00:16:42,493
Is there any chance of switching
to a window seat?

262
00:16:42,696 --> 00:16:44,960
Sorry, we're completely booked
in first.

263
00:16:45,165 --> 00:16:48,134
But these center seats
are really wonderful. See...

264
00:16:48,335 --> 00:16:50,462
...if you push here...
Can I show you?

265
00:16:50,670 --> 00:16:52,399
Sure.

266
00:16:54,107 --> 00:16:56,735
The chair swivels
to the left and the right.

267
00:16:56,943 --> 00:16:59,241
And this converts
to a full-sized dining table...

268
00:16:59,446 --> 00:17:01,209
...during our
Pan Am platinum service...

269
00:17:01,414 --> 00:17:03,974
...with damask linen
and silverware by Fornari...

270
00:17:04,184 --> 00:17:06,414
...so you don't have to eat off a tray.

271
00:17:06,620 --> 00:17:09,282
Again, that's only
for these center seats.

272
00:17:10,257 --> 00:17:11,554
How does that sound?

273
00:17:11,925 --> 00:17:14,553
<i>At that time, when you
traveled first class...</i>

274
00:17:14,761 --> 00:17:18,857
<i>... people would always ask you if you
met someone famous on the flight.</i>

275
00:17:19,065 --> 00:17:20,999
- Mr. Morris.
- Thank you.

276
00:17:21,201 --> 00:17:22,361
You're welcome.

277
00:17:31,945 --> 00:17:36,279
<i>Though he would later accuse me
of engineering this, I didn't.</i>

278
00:17:36,483 --> 00:17:37,848
<i>It just...</i>

279
00:17:38,051 --> 00:17:39,746
<i>... happened.</i>

280
00:17:46,059 --> 00:17:49,119
Reuben. So they...
They record these songs...

281
00:17:49,329 --> 00:17:51,058
...in a studio that I am paying for.

282
00:17:51,264 --> 00:17:53,095
Songs that are recorded for me...

283
00:17:53,300 --> 00:17:54,995
...that they are
contracted to provide.

284
00:17:55,202 --> 00:17:57,170
- Are you with me here?
- Yes, it's just that...

285
00:17:57,370 --> 00:18:00,567
No, it's just that nothing, Irv.
Please, let me finish. They record...

286
00:18:00,774 --> 00:18:04,210
<i>I read an interview where Lanny was
given credit for insisting his butler...</i>

287
00:18:04,411 --> 00:18:08,279
<i>... travel in the same class and stay
at the same hotels as his boss.</i>

288
00:18:08,882 --> 00:18:12,283
<i>The valet's attentiveness
was impressive.</i>

289
00:18:13,253 --> 00:18:16,586
Looks like you'll be having
dinner with Lanny Morris.

290
00:18:19,659 --> 00:18:22,389
- Hello.
- Hi.

291
00:18:32,706 --> 00:18:35,504
We should get a waiter to slide
a matchbook under the airplane.

292
00:18:36,676 --> 00:18:38,234
There we go.

293
00:18:38,445 --> 00:18:40,140
That should hold.

294
00:18:41,681 --> 00:18:42,875
This is my friend Reuben.

295
00:18:43,083 --> 00:18:44,311
- Hi.
- Hi.

296
00:18:44,517 --> 00:18:47,077
And this is also my friend,
technically speaking...

297
00:18:47,287 --> 00:18:49,255
...and business manager, Irv.
- Hi.

298
00:18:51,458 --> 00:18:52,755
My name is Lanny.

299
00:18:57,497 --> 00:18:59,055
And what's your name?

300
00:19:00,533 --> 00:19:02,694
Bonnie. Bonnie Trout.

301
00:19:02,903 --> 00:19:04,234
What do you do, Bonnie?

302
00:19:04,537 --> 00:19:06,004
I teach.

303
00:19:06,206 --> 00:19:07,833
And what do you teach?

304
00:19:08,041 --> 00:19:10,271
- Second grade.
- Well, we have a lot in common.

305
00:19:10,477 --> 00:19:12,968
You teach second grade,
I went to second grade.

306
00:19:13,179 --> 00:19:16,342
- Irv, you went to second grade too?
- Many times.

307
00:19:16,549 --> 00:19:18,016
Tell me, Miss Trout...

308
00:19:18,218 --> 00:19:19,651
I don't mean to be impolite...

309
00:19:19,853 --> 00:19:21,411
...but I was wondering...

310
00:19:21,621 --> 00:19:25,182
...how a second-grade schoolteacher
affords to fly first class.

311
00:19:27,327 --> 00:19:29,522
Well, I have a pass...

312
00:19:29,729 --> 00:19:33,187
...that allows me free use
of the subway on weekends...

313
00:19:33,400 --> 00:19:36,563
...and the hot lunches
at school are only 50 cents.

314
00:19:37,971 --> 00:19:40,405
And I'm the mistress...

315
00:19:40,607 --> 00:19:42,074
...of a wealthy married man...

316
00:19:42,275 --> 00:19:44,903
...and when he and his wife
go on vacation, he treats me...

317
00:19:45,111 --> 00:19:48,274
...to a first-class trip
in the opposite direction.

318
00:19:49,115 --> 00:19:53,552
But look at me, talking only about
myself. What do you do for a living?

319
00:19:54,921 --> 00:19:57,412
I'm a French impressionist
painter out of Tahiti, mainly.

320
00:19:57,624 --> 00:20:00,058
I'm doing that to pay the bills.
My ambition is to be...

321
00:20:00,260 --> 00:20:02,319
...a stockbroker in Paris.

322
00:20:02,629 --> 00:20:04,256
- I don't get it.
- Paul Gauguin.

323
00:20:04,464 --> 00:20:06,432
He gave up being
a successful stockbroker...

324
00:20:06,633 --> 00:20:09,067
...to become a painter
in the South Seas.

325
00:20:10,070 --> 00:20:11,935
You think the average
person knows that?

326
00:20:12,138 --> 00:20:15,505
Well, we're not talking about
the average person, Irv.

327
00:20:18,645 --> 00:20:20,112
<i>In some ways...</i>

328
00:20:20,313 --> 00:20:23,510
<i>... he had never stopped
being a hero to me.</i>

329
00:20:24,351 --> 00:20:28,481
<i>That's why it was impossible
to think he might also be a killer.</i>

330
00:20:35,195 --> 00:20:36,753
Well, this has been great.

331
00:20:36,963 --> 00:20:39,090
I'm gonna see you
inside your apartment.

332
00:20:39,299 --> 00:20:41,767
- There's really no need.
- Don't be silly.

333
00:20:41,968 --> 00:20:43,799
I'm not gonna try to come in.

334
00:20:44,003 --> 00:20:45,527
Promise.

335
00:20:46,306 --> 00:20:48,900
You've been away from your
apartment for how long now?

336
00:20:49,109 --> 00:20:50,770
- Ages.
- You never know if somebody's...

337
00:20:50,977 --> 00:20:52,569
...broken in while you were gone.

338
00:20:52,779 --> 00:20:55,441
I'll just see you inside your door.

339
00:20:56,149 --> 00:20:59,016
Believe me, I'm...
I'm not trying to seduce you.

340
00:20:59,219 --> 00:21:01,187
<i>I have to do the Today show
at 7 a.m.</i>

341
00:21:01,388 --> 00:21:03,788
They want me in Makeup at 6:15.

342
00:21:03,990 --> 00:21:06,254
<i>Bonnie had moved to New York
for the teaching job...</i>

343
00:21:06,459 --> 00:21:08,427
<i>... a little over a year ago.</i>

344
00:21:08,628 --> 00:21:12,655
<i>I had never visited her and had
no idea if this was the right place.</i>

345
00:21:13,933 --> 00:21:15,366
Which floor?

346
00:21:15,969 --> 00:21:17,834
Why...

347
00:21:18,972 --> 00:21:20,200
- Four-D.
- Forty?

348
00:21:20,740 --> 00:21:22,605
It only goes up to six.

349
00:21:25,111 --> 00:21:26,669
Four-D...

350
00:21:26,880 --> 00:21:29,110
Four-D, the fourth floor.

351
00:21:52,105 --> 00:21:53,436
Which way?

352
00:21:54,441 --> 00:21:56,238
- Guess.
- Why?

353
00:21:56,443 --> 00:21:57,705
It's a test.

354
00:21:57,911 --> 00:21:59,435
A test?

355
00:22:01,214 --> 00:22:02,806
Okay.

356
00:22:03,016 --> 00:22:04,415
This way.

357
00:22:08,054 --> 00:22:10,284
So why didn't we take this elevator?

358
00:22:10,490 --> 00:22:12,117
Doesn't work.

359
00:22:15,361 --> 00:22:16,794
Well...

360
00:22:17,664 --> 00:22:19,029
...good night.

361
00:22:19,232 --> 00:22:21,200
No, I'm going to see you
into your apartment.

362
00:22:21,401 --> 00:22:23,926
And then I'm gonna leave you
alone until tomorrow.

363
00:22:41,287 --> 00:22:44,051
I never get which key goes in
which lock the first time.

364
00:22:46,593 --> 00:22:48,891
Hey, looks like they fixed it.

365
00:23:00,273 --> 00:23:01,740
You okay?

366
00:23:01,941 --> 00:23:04,341
Maybe we should turn on a light.

367
00:23:18,091 --> 00:23:19,422
Well...

368
00:23:20,593 --> 00:23:22,151
I'm going to leave you now.

369
00:23:22,362 --> 00:23:25,695
I have Reuben and Irv waiting
in the limousine downstairs...

370
00:23:26,132 --> 00:23:29,101
<i>...and I should get some sleep
for the Today show.</i>

371
00:23:31,337 --> 00:23:32,770
So...

372
00:23:37,544 --> 00:23:39,774
It was lovely to meet you, Bonnie.

373
00:23:59,199 --> 00:24:01,497
<i>By the end of the telethon,
we had no voices.</i>

374
00:24:01,701 --> 00:24:05,296
<i>Thirty-nine hours
of nonstop entertainment.</i>

375
00:24:05,505 --> 00:24:08,338
<i>A telethon was a superhuman feat.</i>

376
00:24:08,541 --> 00:24:11,999
<i>We weren't just heroes,
we were gods.</i>

377
00:24:14,814 --> 00:24:17,612
<i>A couple of the boys were there
to make sure we got out alive...</i>

378
00:24:17,817 --> 00:24:20,149
<i>... to make the flight to New York.</i>

379
00:24:24,023 --> 00:24:26,958
Everyone. Listen. Listen.

380
00:24:27,160 --> 00:24:29,253
Gentlemen. Gentlemen, please.

381
00:24:29,662 --> 00:24:32,688
Gentlemen, if I could just
have your attention.

382
00:24:33,066 --> 00:24:34,897
Everyone, Mr. Collins
and Mr. Morris...

383
00:24:35,101 --> 00:24:37,365
...will answer questions
at the press conference...

384
00:24:37,570 --> 00:24:39,265
...at the Palace Del Sol.

385
00:24:39,472 --> 00:24:41,440
Gentlemen, there will be
plenty of time...

386
00:24:41,641 --> 00:24:45,099
...to answer your questions
at the Palace Del Sol.

387
00:24:45,311 --> 00:24:48,371
Thank you, we will answer your
questions at the press conference.

388
00:24:48,581 --> 00:24:50,549
Thank you for coming.

389
00:24:56,556 --> 00:24:59,548
<i>We had a full police escort, along
with bodyguards who were there...</i>

390
00:24:59,759 --> 00:25:02,660
<i>... to protect us from any thoughts
we might have of going AWOI...</i>

391
00:25:02,862 --> 00:25:04,625
<i>... prior to this press conference.</i>

392
00:25:04,831 --> 00:25:07,959
<i>A pair of New Jersey's finest
walked on either side of us...</i>

393
00:25:08,167 --> 00:25:10,727
<i>... as we entered
the lobby of the hotel.</i>

394
00:25:10,937 --> 00:25:13,667
<i>It was an indication of how
legitimate the Mob had gone...</i>

395
00:25:13,873 --> 00:25:16,068
<i>... that they could
bring in the local police...</i>

396
00:25:16,276 --> 00:25:18,744
<i>... to guard the façade of their racket.</i>

397
00:25:19,312 --> 00:25:23,442
<i>The local chief was a man
named Jack Scaglia.</i>

398
00:25:23,650 --> 00:25:26,551
And of course, the two
gentlemen on my right...

399
00:25:26,753 --> 00:25:30,052
...who need no introduction,
have come here directly...

400
00:25:30,256 --> 00:25:33,919
...from their record-breaking
polio telethon in Miami, Florida.

401
00:25:34,994 --> 00:25:38,452
So the first thing I'd like to announce
is that Mr. Sanmarco...

402
00:25:38,931 --> 00:25:40,193
<i>I wish I could tell you...</i>

403
00:25:40,400 --> 00:25:42,960
<i>... that Sally Sanmarco
was a slim, 6-foot-6 guy...</i>

404
00:25:43,169 --> 00:25:46,161
<i>... who looked like a prince
and spoke with an English accent.</i>

405
00:25:46,372 --> 00:25:48,738
<i>Then I wouldn't be
falling back on the stereotype.</i>

406
00:25:49,042 --> 00:25:52,603
<i>The trouble was, Sally was
straight out of central casting.</i>

407
00:25:53,446 --> 00:25:55,471
<i>A gangster
who looked and talked...</i>

408
00:25:55,682 --> 00:25:58,310
<i>... just like you would expect
from the movies.</i>

409
00:25:58,518 --> 00:26:01,112
How did it feel to raise
all that money for polio?

410
00:26:01,654 --> 00:26:03,849
It felt great. It felt really great.

411
00:26:04,057 --> 00:26:06,924
<i>From a publicity angle, and in
terms of giving him legitimacy...</i>

412
00:26:07,126 --> 00:26:09,356
<i>... this was a huge coup for Sally.</i>

413
00:26:09,562 --> 00:26:12,030
<i>Like I said, we were gods.</i>

414
00:26:13,333 --> 00:26:16,928
<i>We'd only been in the New York area
for an hour or so, during which time...</i>

415
00:26:17,136 --> 00:26:19,900
<i>... we were constantly watched
by police and reporters...</i>

416
00:26:20,106 --> 00:26:22,836
<i>... which ended up being
a good thing for us.</i>

417
00:26:23,042 --> 00:26:25,476
We got you our best bridal suite.

418
00:26:25,978 --> 00:26:27,969
Fucking nice, huh?

419
00:26:29,115 --> 00:26:31,811
People talk about having fancy
apartments and hotel rooms...

420
00:26:32,018 --> 00:26:34,111
...on the West Side of Manhattan.
What do they see?

421
00:26:34,320 --> 00:26:37,483
Fucking New Jersey.
Here, you see New York City.

422
00:26:44,731 --> 00:26:47,165
<i>Unfortunately,
Vince and I were acquainted...</i>

423
00:26:47,366 --> 00:26:51,666
<i>... with the dead girl in the bathroom
of our hotel suite in New Jersey.</i>

424
00:26:52,205 --> 00:26:55,436
<i>Her last name was O'Flaherty.</i>

425
00:26:55,875 --> 00:26:59,003
<i>Her first name was Maureen.</i>

426
00:26:59,245 --> 00:27:02,908
<i>Karen, we decided to trade
apartments, not identities.</i>

427
00:27:03,116 --> 00:27:04,640
<i>Why didn't you make up a name?</i>

428
00:27:04,851 --> 00:27:07,376
Bonnie, I was looking
at a five-hour flight.

429
00:27:07,587 --> 00:27:10,715
I didn't wanna make up a life story
that wasn't attached to anything.

430
00:27:10,923 --> 00:27:14,415
Well, I returned the offense.
I got to pretend I was you.

431
00:27:14,627 --> 00:27:16,185
<i>- What?
- You received a package.</i>

432
00:27:16,395 --> 00:27:18,693
Messenger service.
I signed your name.

433
00:27:18,898 --> 00:27:21,526
- Who's it from?
- No address. Want me to open it?

434
00:27:21,734 --> 00:27:23,258
- Sure.
- That's good. I already did.

435
00:27:23,469 --> 00:27:24,731
It's a manuscript.

436
00:27:24,937 --> 00:27:27,371
"Excerpt From the Memoirs of...

437
00:27:27,573 --> 00:27:29,336
...Lanny Morris."

438
00:27:29,542 --> 00:27:33,535
Hey, all your dreams are coming true.
He's writing you love letters already.

439
00:27:33,746 --> 00:27:35,714
Bonnie, I need
to know what he's written.

440
00:27:35,915 --> 00:27:39,874
- Well, I'll send it to you.
- Now. Before he calls me tomorrow.

441
00:27:42,121 --> 00:27:45,056
- Please?
- All right.

442
00:27:46,459 --> 00:27:48,290
All right.

443
00:27:48,494 --> 00:27:49,927
Here we go.

444
00:27:52,298 --> 00:27:56,234
"Let me explain to you why two
very famous guys just finishing...

445
00:27:56,435 --> 00:28:00,565
...a nationally broadcast telethon
ended up in New Jersey."

446
00:28:05,211 --> 00:28:10,410
<i>For years, the Palace Del Sol was
one of the centers of Mob prosperity.</i>

447
00:28:10,616 --> 00:28:13,608
<i>Needless to say, a major
headliner in the showroom...</i>

448
00:28:13,820 --> 00:28:16,983
<i>... helped legitimize
the entire operation.</i>

449
00:28:17,190 --> 00:28:18,919
Give her a kiss. Yeah, beautiful.

450
00:28:19,125 --> 00:28:22,151
One more, guys. That's it.
That's great. Thank you.

451
00:28:22,361 --> 00:28:24,795
<i>Vince and I needed help
in keeping us up all the time...</i>

452
00:28:24,997 --> 00:28:27,192
<i>... and in the way of thinking
in the '50s...</i>

453
00:28:27,400 --> 00:28:29,630
<i>... anything you didn't take
with a needle was okay.</i>

454
00:28:29,836 --> 00:28:33,499
<i>It wasn't "serious" serious.
It was like running a red light.</i>

455
00:28:33,706 --> 00:28:38,575
<i>Everyone used bennies. Vince added
them to his morning coffee like sugar.</i>

456
00:28:43,549 --> 00:28:45,608
