00:44:19,192 --> 00:44:22,286
Well, as I've always understood
this company's policy...

685
00:44:22,495 --> 00:44:24,520
...while the book is being written...

686
00:44:24,731 --> 00:44:29,168
...the relationship between the author
and editor is sacrosanct.

687
00:44:30,236 --> 00:44:32,329
This isn't your typical book deal.

688
00:44:32,739 --> 00:44:36,698
We've really just leased
an oil well called Vince Collins...

689
00:44:36,910 --> 00:44:40,243
...and granted Ms. O'Connor
the right to tap.

690
00:44:40,480 --> 00:44:43,938
I think we have a responsibility to...

691
00:44:44,417 --> 00:44:46,715
...monitor the drilling.

692
00:45:09,943 --> 00:45:12,434
- Hello.
- Mrs. O'Flaherty?

693
00:45:13,046 --> 00:45:14,536
Yes.

694
00:45:14,781 --> 00:45:18,410
My name's O'Connor.
I'm the one writing the book.

695
00:45:31,531 --> 00:45:34,728
The book will be
centered around Vince Collins.

696
00:45:34,934 --> 00:45:37,767
I'll be asking him a lot of questions.

697
00:45:37,971 --> 00:45:42,999
I wanted to know if there were any
you'd like to have answered yourself.

698
00:45:46,913 --> 00:45:51,441
Maureen and I planted this tree
on her fifth birthday.

699
00:45:52,919 --> 00:45:56,355
Father did most of the digging,
of course.

700
00:45:57,424 --> 00:45:59,585
She'd be 38.

701
00:46:00,460 --> 00:46:03,486
I'm 59 myself.

702
00:46:05,799 --> 00:46:08,359
If she were alive now...

703
00:46:09,769 --> 00:46:13,330
...we'd be talking about things,
back and forth...

704
00:46:13,540 --> 00:46:15,337
...like two women.

705
00:46:16,009 --> 00:46:18,341
Like you and I are doing.

706
00:46:23,983 --> 00:46:26,178
And Maureen's father?

707
00:46:27,187 --> 00:46:29,712
Frank died six years ago.

708
00:46:30,356 --> 00:46:32,483
He took his own life.

709
00:46:33,093 --> 00:46:36,153
One night, just before he died...

710
00:46:36,363 --> 00:46:39,491
...he dug up the earth
around this tree...

711
00:46:39,999 --> 00:46:42,797
...he took the urn
with Maureen's ashes in it...

712
00:46:43,002 --> 00:46:45,732
...and spread them around its roots.

713
00:46:47,640 --> 00:46:51,406
So this is my daughter.

714
00:46:53,046 --> 00:46:55,640
This is what I have of her.

715
00:47:02,622 --> 00:47:05,352
<i>- Are you Catholic?
- My... My mother was.</i>

716
00:47:06,126 --> 00:47:08,651
<i>Then you will understand
my dilemma.</i>

717
00:47:08,862 --> 00:47:12,559
<i>Our faith offers an afterlife.</i>

718
00:47:13,767 --> 00:47:16,099
A daughter needs her mother.

719
00:47:17,203 --> 00:47:23,199
So I have to live out this life
as far from sin as I can manage.

720
00:47:26,146 --> 00:47:28,774
<i>I'll never see my husband again.</i>

721
00:47:29,315 --> 00:47:31,715
<i>He's consigned himself to hell.</i>

722
00:47:34,154 --> 00:47:37,612
<i>But what if Maureen
killed herself too?</i>

723
00:47:41,327 --> 00:47:43,955
She's in hell, with my husband.

724
00:47:44,164 --> 00:47:48,294
The life I'm trying to lead
will bring me to heaven's grace...

725
00:47:49,369 --> 00:47:52,736
...only to hear
their screams of torment.

726
00:47:54,274 --> 00:47:56,504
<i>Chief Scaglia,
you were in the hotel room...</i>

727
00:47:56,709 --> 00:47:59,872
<i>... when they found
Maureen's body in the tub.</i>

728
00:48:00,313 --> 00:48:04,215
So was Sally, so was Lanny,
so was Vince.

729
00:48:05,685 --> 00:48:09,849
And there was also
a PR lady there from the hotel.

730
00:48:10,256 --> 00:48:11,814
How do you think she died?

731
00:48:12,492 --> 00:48:15,552
She died in an auto accident
two weeks later. It was terrible.

732
00:48:19,032 --> 00:48:20,226
No, Maureen.

733
00:48:20,433 --> 00:48:23,095
- How did Maureen die?
- She drowned.

734
00:48:23,303 --> 00:48:25,100
- Why?
- What do you mean, why?

735
00:48:25,305 --> 00:48:27,830
You and I take baths all the time.
We don't drown in them.

736
00:48:28,041 --> 00:48:31,067
You and I do not mix
sleeping pills with booze.

737
00:48:31,277 --> 00:48:34,212
- She committed suicide?
- Overdose is the official story.

738
00:48:34,414 --> 00:48:38,248
What's the official story on the fact
that the staff of the hotel in Miami...

739
00:48:38,451 --> 00:48:41,511
<i>... all seemed to know she delivered
room service to the boys' suite...</i>

740
00:48:41,721 --> 00:48:44,554
...three days before
and was never seen alive again?

741
00:48:44,757 --> 00:48:46,088
What happened to her?

742
00:48:46,292 --> 00:48:48,760
How did she end up
in a hotel room in New Jersey?

743
00:48:48,962 --> 00:48:52,830
Sally never had any problem
moving girls around. Okay?

744
00:48:53,032 --> 00:48:54,226
He had two hotels.

745
00:48:54,434 --> 00:48:56,425
- So Sally arranged it?
- No, I don't think so.

746
00:48:56,636 --> 00:48:59,503
You see, she was brought up there
as a reward for the boys...

747
00:48:59,706 --> 00:49:02,368
...and I think she started
to party just a little too early.

748
00:49:02,575 --> 00:49:05,066
She was a student.
This was a summer job.

749
00:49:05,278 --> 00:49:06,540
Listen to me...

750
00:49:06,980 --> 00:49:12,919
...the Palace Del Sol was very
important to Sally, okay?

751
00:49:13,119 --> 00:49:16,282
He launched his new wing...

752
00:49:16,489 --> 00:49:19,788
...with a push
from Lanny and Vince...

753
00:49:19,993 --> 00:49:25,625
...and this stupid girl
shows up dead.

754
00:49:25,932 --> 00:49:30,460
She's not gonna come back.
We do the best thing for all of us.

755
00:49:30,670 --> 00:49:35,130
We speed up the investigation
and we cremate her. Okay?

756
00:49:35,341 --> 00:49:37,536
End of story.

757
00:49:40,346 --> 00:49:43,941
- Here you are.
- Here's your lobster.

758
00:49:44,150 --> 00:49:47,085
- Enjoy.
- Looks great.

759
00:49:48,521 --> 00:49:52,287
"Sally said, 'I'll have them send you
up your own shipment of lobsters.

760
00:49:52,492 --> 00:49:54,517
<i>You like lobster?"'</i>

761
00:49:55,094 --> 00:49:58,393
<i>We said we did
because we really did.</i>

762
00:49:59,165 --> 00:50:02,066
<i>You shouldn't have done that,
Stanley. I don't eat lobster.</i>

763
00:50:05,004 --> 00:50:07,404
<i>Were there any signs of violence
on her body?</i>

764
00:50:07,607 --> 00:50:11,907
No, no. There were some
small scratches on the torso.

765
00:50:13,813 --> 00:50:19,183
<i>Why did my daughter die?
Did she kill herself?</i>

766
00:50:20,086 --> 00:50:23,647
<i>What had they done to her
that would make her do that?</i>

767
00:50:26,259 --> 00:50:28,489
<i>What had they done?</i>

768
00:50:33,433 --> 00:50:35,697
<i>Once upon a time...</i>

769
00:50:35,902 --> 00:50:39,565
<i>... when terrible things
happened to people...</i>

770
00:50:39,772 --> 00:50:42,332
<i>... they were left as a mystery.</i>

771
00:50:44,510 --> 00:50:47,741
<i>Even the tabloids kept a distance.</i>

772
00:50:53,152 --> 00:50:58,920
<i>Some things were allowed
to be left just the way they were.</i>

773
00:51:07,734 --> 00:51:09,565
Any trouble with the directions
I gave you?

774
00:51:09,769 --> 00:51:13,205
- Only the parts where I had to turn.
- Sorry.

775
00:51:14,107 --> 00:51:16,507
It's the price of seclusion.

776
00:51:21,581 --> 00:51:23,572
You haven't switched over
to cassette?

777
00:51:23,783 --> 00:51:27,651
- Actually, it's my dad's.
- And what does he do?

778
00:51:29,022 --> 00:51:31,149
He was a journalist too.

779
00:51:32,225 --> 00:51:34,557
He did a big story on you once.

780
00:51:34,761 --> 00:51:37,423
Followed a little girl who had polio.

781
00:51:37,764 --> 00:51:40,028
You took her under your wing...

782
00:51:41,167 --> 00:51:43,499
...and now she's interviewing you.

783
00:51:47,073 --> 00:51:50,304
He must be proud that his daughter's
making such a name for herself.

784
00:51:50,843 --> 00:51:52,936
I'd like to think so.

785
00:51:54,147 --> 00:51:57,742
- He died last year.
- Sorry to hear that.

786
00:51:59,385 --> 00:52:03,014
- Would you like some coffee?
- Sure.

787
00:52:10,096 --> 00:52:11,961
Are you alone here?

788
00:52:12,165 --> 00:52:16,192
Yes. The thought of having live-in help
is a little poisonous to me.

789
00:52:16,402 --> 00:52:17,801
Why's that?

790
00:52:18,004 --> 00:52:19,904
Well, I'd have to talk to them...

791
00:52:20,106 --> 00:52:22,540
...ask them how
their family was doing...

792
00:52:22,742 --> 00:52:25,370
...hear about this and that,
introduce them to the guests...

793
00:52:25,578 --> 00:52:28,240
...and tell them
how their family was doing.

794
00:52:28,448 --> 00:52:32,145
All so that I would
seem to be a nice guy...

795
00:52:32,351 --> 00:52:33,943
...which is an awful lot of work...

796
00:52:34,153 --> 00:52:36,587
...considering what I cherish
most in life these days...

797
00:52:36,789 --> 00:52:38,848
...is not to have to be Vince Collins.

798
00:52:39,058 --> 00:52:40,491
No Reuben in your life?

799
00:52:41,794 --> 00:52:43,785
How do you know about Reuben?

800
00:52:44,163 --> 00:52:47,690
He was in a lot of the material
I've been looking at.

801
00:52:47,900 --> 00:52:49,367
No, I never had a Reuben.

802
00:52:49,569 --> 00:52:51,935
Lanny always paid him directly.
He was Lanny's man.

803
00:52:52,138 --> 00:52:53,605
Right.

804
00:52:56,008 --> 00:52:58,067
You know, what I like is to...

805
00:52:58,277 --> 00:52:59,869
...read...

806
00:53:00,980 --> 00:53:02,379
...think.

807
00:53:02,582 --> 00:53:04,777
It's to have the freedom...

808
00:53:04,984 --> 00:53:07,475
...to get up and leave
without telling anyone about it...

809
00:53:07,687 --> 00:53:09,587
...any time of day.

810
00:53:11,591 --> 00:53:13,923
Or even having to say goodbye.

811
00:53:16,129 --> 00:53:20,088
To be backstage, surrounded
by acrobats, actors, magicians...

812
00:53:20,299 --> 00:53:22,164
...it was intoxicating.

813
00:53:22,368 --> 00:53:24,199
You know, I was only 12 years old.

814
00:53:24,403 --> 00:53:26,030
That's a...

815
00:53:26,239 --> 00:53:27,763
That's a pretty impressionable age.

816
00:53:27,974 --> 00:53:31,034
<i>- To hear all these stories of touring...
- My father always told me...</i>

817
00:53:31,244 --> 00:53:34,736
<i>... that nothing had meaning
unless it could be put on the record.</i>

818
00:53:36,215 --> 00:53:38,240
<i>Yet things had changed.</i>

819
00:53:39,385 --> 00:53:41,478
<i>As Vince had pointed out
at our first meeting...</i>

820
00:53:41,687 --> 00:53:45,987
<i>... it had become fashionable
to put yourself into the story.</i>

821
00:53:46,659 --> 00:53:49,992
<i>The question became
how far you were prepared to go.</i>

822
00:54:13,286 --> 00:54:17,620
- Excuse me. That's not mine.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

823
00:54:20,560 --> 00:54:22,755
Aren't you Miss Trout?

824
00:54:22,962 --> 00:54:25,590
We've met,
on the plane to New York.

825
00:54:25,798 --> 00:54:26,992
- Reuben.
- Excuse me, sir.

826
00:54:27,200 --> 00:54:29,964
Can I leave you
for just a second, please?

827
00:54:33,739 --> 00:54:36,469
I'm so deeply sorry, Miss Trout,
the way you were treated.

828
00:54:36,676 --> 00:54:40,703
- He could have left a note.
- Of course.

829
00:54:41,981 --> 00:54:45,542
Miss Trout, I would like you
to understand something.

830
00:54:46,385 --> 00:54:51,118
I have a great loyalty to Mr. Morris.
He's treated me very well.

831
00:54:51,324 --> 00:54:53,019
I'm very grateful.

832
00:54:54,427 --> 00:54:57,453
He has done wonderful things
for many people...

833
00:54:57,663 --> 00:55:02,623
...and I have been privileged
to work for him.

834
00:55:04,203 --> 00:55:06,501
But I do have certain principles...

835
00:55:06,706 --> 00:55:10,938
...especially about how women
are to be treated and respected.

836
00:55:11,344 --> 00:55:16,748
Mr. Morris can be very attentive,
but once he has a woman...

837
00:55:17,917 --> 00:55:20,715
Oh, God, I think
it's almost a sickness.

838
00:55:22,722 --> 00:55:24,553
When he left you that morning...

839
00:55:24,757 --> 00:55:27,385
...you may have felt bad,
but believe me, Miss Trout...

840
00:55:27,593 --> 00:55:29,424
...to have him out of your life...

841
00:55:29,629 --> 00:55:32,325
...is the best thing that
could have happened to you.

842
00:55:33,399 --> 00:55:37,062
At that point, you may have felt
your life was wounded.

843
00:55:38,604 --> 00:55:40,435
It wasn't.

844
00:55:41,307 --> 00:55:42,569
It was saved.

845
00:55:51,684 --> 00:55:54,050
<i>Vince, I was very clear about this
from the beginning.</i>

846
00:55:54,253 --> 00:55:55,845
<i>I'm not out to play games with you.</i>

847
00:55:56,055 --> 00:55:58,421
<i>This is why you're being paid
a huge amount of money.</i>

848
00:55:59,425 --> 00:56:01,256
<i>This isn't entirely about money,
you know.</i>

849
00:56:01,460 --> 00:56:04,020
A million dollars is more than
the gross of your last film.

850
00:56:05,331 --> 00:56:07,595
I was somehow
under the impression that my life...

851
00:56:07,800 --> 00:56:10,769
...might have been of more than
passing interest.

852
00:56:10,970 --> 00:56:13,962
But if my fleeting encounter with
a girl named Maureen O'Flaherty...

853
00:56:14,173 --> 00:56:17,108
...is all you really want to talk about,
then that's what we'll do.

854
00:56:18,611 --> 00:56:20,909
I have to make an appearance
at the clinic tomorrow.

855
00:56:21,113 --> 00:56:23,240
We can come back
and talk after that.

856
00:56:24,283 --> 00:56:26,012
It's Wonderland.

857
00:56:26,218 --> 00:56:27,810
I imagine you might remember that.

858
00:56:42,001 --> 00:56:46,131
<i>He was right.
I did remember Wonderland.</i>

859
00:56:47,006 --> 00:56:48,735
- You ready?
- Ready.

860
00:56:48,941 --> 00:56:54,208
<i>When I was a girl, the entire hospital
was devoted to children with polio.</i>

861
00:56:55,881 --> 00:56:59,078
<i>Since that time,
it had become a clinic for kids...</i>

862
00:56:59,285 --> 00:57:02,516
<i>... with a variety of different
physical handicaps.</i>

863
00:57:06,125 --> 00:57:09,492
<i>Once a year, the children
would put on a pageant...</i>

864
00:57:09,695 --> 00:57:13,028
<i>... playing different characters
from Alice in Wonderland.</i>

865
00:57:14,033 --> 00:57:16,467
<i>Vince, in his continuing support
of the hospital...</i>

866
00:57:16,669 --> 00:57:19,160
<i>... had hired a band and a singer.</i>

867
00:57:26,645 --> 00:57:28,340
Who is that?

868
00:57:28,547 --> 00:57:32,381
I don't know.
She's good, whoever she is.

869
00:57:43,829 --> 00:57:47,060
Karen, do you mind if we start
this conversation tomorrow?

870
00:57:47,266 --> 00:57:50,895
I'm just...
I'm not feeling all that well.

871
00:57:51,570 --> 00:57:53,060
- Vince...
- In fact, it won't make...

872
00:57:53,272 --> 00:57:55,536
...any difference over there.
The office is closed.

873
00:57:55,741 --> 00:57:56,935
They've been working late.

874
00:57:57,143 --> 00:57:59,134
Then they've been working
much too hard.

875
00:58:00,479 --> 00:58:03,107
First thing tomorrow. First thing.

876
00:58:10,089 --> 00:58:12,489
I hope your editors were reasonable.

877
00:58:12,691 --> 00:58:15,660
Reasonable? No, they weren't.

878
00:58:15,861 --> 00:58:17,920
We can go as late as you like.

879
00:58:18,130 --> 00:58:19,392
That's good.

880
00:58:19,598 --> 00:58:21,031
It might take us
into the evening.

881
00:58:21,233 --> 00:58:23,201
I had a feeling
that might be the case.

882
00:58:23,702 --> 00:58:26,364
So I've ordered a hot and cold
smorgasbord to be brought in.

883
00:58:26,572 --> 00:58:28,039
We can work through dinner.

884
00:58:28,240 --> 00:58:30,435
- We'll be having company?
- Yes.

885
00:58:31,911 --> 00:58:33,435
I have...

886
00:58:33,646 --> 00:58:35,341
...a surprise for you.

887
00:58:36,282 --> 00:58:39,046
Actually, this is a fairly big deal
for me as well.

888
00:58:40,252 --> 00:58:42,652
I've asked Lanny to join us today.

889
00:58:43,956 --> 00:58:44,980
Lanny?

890
00:58:46,358 --> 00:58:48,485
Well, this is something.

891
00:58:49,361 --> 00:58:52,387
Neuman and Newberry will certainly
be getting their money's worth.

892
00:58:52,965 --> 00:58:55,263
I thought that if I was
going to discuss something...

893
00:58:55,468 --> 00:58:57,265
...that had such an impact
on our lives...

894
00:58:57,470 --> 00:59:00,064
...it would be fair for Lanny
to hear what I had to say.

895
00:59:00,773 --> 00:59:02,468
Given that we've
never talked about it.

896
00:59:02,675 --> 00:59:05,337
I'm sure I'll have lots to ask him.
When is he coming?

897
00:59:05,544 --> 00:59:07,478
He should be here any minute now.

898
00:59:08,047 --> 00:59:09,878
This is very exciting.

899
00:59:10,449 --> 00:59:12,246
Shit.

900
00:59:26,899 --> 00:59:29,129
<i>- Yes?
- Bonnie, I have to talk fast.</i>

901
00:59:29,335 --> 00:59:32,395
I need you to do exactly as I tell you
and I can't tell you why, okay?

902
00:59:32,605 --> 00:59:33,833
<i>Sure.</i>

903
00:59:34,573 --> 00:59:36,939
Excuse me, that might actually
be him now.

904
00:59:37,977 --> 00:59:39,672
Yes, hello?

905
00:59:52,057 --> 00:59:53,615
Yes, thank you.

906
00:59:55,361 --> 00:59:56,692
That was my office.

907
00:59:56,896 --> 00:59:59,364
There's a woman...
A friend, a relative of yours?

908
00:59:59,565 --> 01:00:01,965
She said she called
on a number you gave her.

909
01:00:02,635 --> 01:00:04,535
She's gonna call back.

910
01:00:11,010 --> 01:00:13,137
<i>- Yes?
- Hi, kiddo.</i>

911
01:00:13,345 --> 01:00:16,473
<i>Listen, your brother Clifford
has just been rushed to the hospital.</i>

912
01:00:16,682 --> 01:00:18,445
<i>He was doing construction
when a thing...</i>

913
01:00:18,651 --> 01:00:20,448
<i>- A steel girder?
- That's it.</i>

914
01:00:20,653 --> 01:00:23,144
<i>You better come to the city
and make your peace with him.</i>

915
01:00:23,355 --> 01:00:25,516
<i>You're booked on the next
flight to San Francisco.</i>

916
01:00:25,724 --> 01:00:27,885
<i>I'm waiting here for you
in front of the terminal.</i>

917
01:00:28,394 --> 01:00:30,794
They reserved me a seat
on the next flight to San Francisco.

918
01:00:30,996 --> 01:00:32,293
- I'll drive you there.
- No, no.

919
01:00:32,498 --> 01:00:35,558
Sharon is waiting at the airport for me.
You can't stand Lanny up.

920
01:00:35,768 --> 01:00:38,202
Please give him
my deepest apologies.

921
01:00:47,246 --> 01:00:50,443
- Hey.
- Please, I can explain.

922
01:00:51,283 --> 01:00:53,547
You've broken the law,
Bonnie-fucking-Trout.

923
01:00:53,752 --> 01:00:55,583
You've assumed
another person's identity...

924
01:00:55,788 --> 01:00:58,154
...to get information
from a business competitor.

925
01:00:58,357 --> 01:01:01,019
Obviously I lied about who I was.
I'm sorry.

926
01:01:01,227 --> 01:01:03,422
It was a huge untruth.
It wasn't planned.

927
01:01:03,629 --> 01:01:08,157
I was just freaked out about
suddenly being on the plane with...

928
01:01:09,201 --> 01:01:10,566
With you...

929
01:01:10,769 --> 01:01:13,067
How did you get the seat
behind me on the plane?

930
01:01:13,272 --> 01:01:14,899
- It was pure coincidence.
- Bullshit!

931
01:01:15,107 --> 01:01:16,540
It's true.

932
01:01:20,579 --> 01:01:24,310
How could you..? How could you have
just left me at the hotel like that?

933
01:01:24,717 --> 01:01:25,911
You were asleep.

934
01:01:26,118 --> 01:01:29,315
Reuben woke me to say
I had to be a substitute performer...

935
01:01:29,521 --> 01:01:33,753
...at a charity concert at the Hollywood
Bowl. I had to get the first flight out.

936
01:01:33,959 --> 01:01:35,517
You could have left a note
or called.

937
01:01:35,728 --> 01:01:37,787
- I did leave you a note.
- Where?

938
01:01:39,632 --> 01:01:43,227
I don't know why we're even talking
about this. I don't like you.

939
01:01:43,435 --> 01:01:46,370
All right? I wish we had never met.

940
01:01:52,244 --> 01:01:53,438
Hello, Vince.

941
01:01:54,213 --> 01:01:55,908
What the fuck's going on?

942
01:01:57,850 --> 01:02:00,512
Vince, a few days after we first met...

943
01:02:00,719 --> 01:02:03,552
...I found myself next to Lanny
on a flight to New York.

944
01:02:03,756 --> 01:02:05,383
It was a complete coincidence.

945
01:02:05,591 --> 01:02:07,252
- He asked my name...
- And she lied.

946
01:02:07,459 --> 01:02:10,724
I had just finished reading the first
chapter of Lanny's own biography.

947
01:02:10,929 --> 01:02:14,330
His lawyers had let me see it in the
hope of discouraging our own project.

948
01:02:14,533 --> 01:02:17,058
As a reflex, since I knew he
would view me as the enemy...

949
01:02:17,269 --> 01:02:18,896
...I gave him the name of a friend...

950
01:02:19,104 --> 01:02:21,197
...whose apartment I was
staying at in Manhattan.

951
01:02:21,407 --> 01:02:24,706
I thought I just had to get through
the awkwardness of the flight itself...

952
01:02:24,910 --> 01:02:26,901
...but the trouble is...
- You slept with him.

953
01:02:28,781 --> 01:02:32,148
- Vince...
- You slept with my ex-partner.

954
01:02:33,619 --> 01:02:34,847
Technically.

955
01:02:36,855 --> 01:02:39,449
Doesn't sound like things were
particularly technical.

956
01:03:01,280 --> 01:03:03,271
Now, you listen to me, sweetheart.

957
01:03:04,083 --> 01:03:07,985
Vince doesn't always do
what's best for Vince.

958
01:03:08,187 --> 01:03:10,781
That's why he needed me
here today.

959
01:03:11,490 --> 01:03:15,449
The story of this girl is the
most painful thing in his life.

960
01:03:15,661 --> 01:03:17,822
What happened to her, Lanny?

961
01:03:18,997 --> 01:03:20,897
Well, you're not gonna find out.

962
01:03:21,834 --> 01:03:23,392
Not now.

963
01:03:24,136 --> 01:03:26,297
Not after what you've done to him.

964
01:03:35,681 --> 01:03:37,308
Vince.

965
01:03:37,516 --> 01:03:38,813
Oh, shit.

966
01:03:40,753 --> 01:03:42,812
Vince...

967
01:03:43,021 --> 01:03:44,989
...I made a terrible mistake
in New York.

968
01:03:45,190 --> 01:03:48,557
I apologize to you
more than I know how to say.

969
01:03:48,761 --> 01:03:50,991
I'm so sorry.

970
01:04:00,806 --> 01:04:04,105
Vince, the realization
of your life story...

971
01:04:04,309 --> 01:04:06,937
...shouldn't be threatened
because of my failings.

972
01:04:09,148 --> 01:04:11,878
Please let me continue
to work with you again.

973
01:04:13,085 --> 01:04:15,417
I'll help you tell your story right.

974
01:04:18,023 --> 01:04:19,957
Come back tonight.

975
01:04:22,027 --> 01:04:23,688
Let me think about it.

976
01:04:36,341 --> 01:04:40,209
- How do you like the wine?
- It's magnificent. What is it?

977
01:04:40,412 --> 01:04:42,903
1961 Haut-Brion.

978
01:04:43,115 --> 01:04:44,844
People make a big deal of 1959...

979
01:04:45,050 --> 01:04:48,383
...but I don't think there'll be
a year as special as 1961.

980
01:04:49,021 --> 01:04:51,785
It was a great year for French wines.

981
01:04:55,127 --> 01:04:57,061
Will you join me?

982
01:04:57,896 --> 01:04:59,488
What are they?

983
01:05:00,032 --> 01:05:04,196
They're like very mild-mannered
Quaaludes.

984
01:05:04,436 --> 01:05:06,529
Must've done a few of those
in your time, right?

985
01:05:08,006 --> 01:05:09,735
Are you sure they're okay
with alcohol?

986
01:05:09,942 --> 01:05:13,469
Oh, they're even better with alcohol.
Believe me, I'd know.

987
01:05:19,685 --> 01:05:21,778
Come on in, honey. The water's fine.

988
01:05:22,855 --> 01:05:27,690
<i>All my life, I've had this idea
that I could always be in control.</i>

989
01:05:28,293 --> 01:05:30,227
<i>Ever since I was sick,
I had this sense...</i>

990
01:05:30,429 --> 01:05:33,592
<i>... that I could make my body
do anything I wanted.</i>

991
01:05:33,799 --> 01:05:35,460
<i>If I could will my polio away...</i>

992
01:05:35,667 --> 01:05:39,125
<i>... I'd certainly be able to will away
the effect of any drug.</i>

993
01:05:52,885 --> 01:05:56,548
Do you mind if I close the drapes?
The sun's in my eyes.

994
01:05:58,323 --> 01:06:00,188
It's moonlight.

995
01:06:01,627 --> 01:06:03,151
Go ahead.

996
01:07:05,090 --> 01:07:07,149
I remember you.

997
01:07:07,759 --> 01:07:09,488
You're Alice.

998
01:07:10,128 --> 01:07:12,289
In Wonderland.

999
01:07:12,998 --> 01:07:15,193
Oh, I don't know.

1000
01:07:15,400 --> 01:07:17,800
I'm really stoned
out of my head already.

1001
01:07:19,104 --> 01:07:20,662
Is it good?

1002
01:07:26,211 --> 01:07:30,307
Jesus, Vince. It's like monster grass.

1003
01:07:30,515 --> 01:07:32,779
Do you get this stuff all the time?

1004
01:07:32,985 --> 01:07:34,976
All the time.

1005
01:07:44,329 --> 01:07:46,763
You're Alice.

1006
01:07:49,601 --> 01:07:51,262
You're so beautiful.

1007
01:08:20,298 --> 01:08:22,198
She's ours.

1008
01:08:22,901 --> 01:08:24,892
Isn't that so, Alice?

1009
01:08:26,405 --> 01:08:28,270
I'm yours.

1010
01:08:52,573 --> 01:08:54,404
I like you.

1011
01:09:07,054 --> 01:09:10,319
<i>I had always been fascinated by how
some women could cross the line...</i>

1012
01:09:10,524 --> 01:09:15,154
<i>... between who they were and who
they would let themselves become.</i>

1013
01:09:15,863 --> 01:09:17,558
<i>Maureen...</i>

1014
01:09:18,299 --> 01:09:20,130
<i>... Alice...</i>

1015
01:09:20,801 --> 01:09:22,359
<i>... and now...</i>

1016
01:09:22,570 --> 01:09:24,128
<i>... me.</i>

1017
01:09:30,644 --> 01:09:31,975
Morning.

1018
01:09:32,179 --> 01:09:35,478
That was not a Quaalude you
gave me. I've had Quaaludes.

1019
01:09:36,784 --> 01:09:38,115
I said it was like a Quaalude.

1020
01:09:38,319 --> 01:09:40,685
And you didn't take one yourself.
You palmed the pill.

1021
01:09:40,888 --> 01:09:42,879
Somebody had to drive.

1022
01:09:43,858 --> 01:09:45,655
Don't worry, you won't get pregnant.

1023
01:09:45,860 --> 01:09:47,691
Not from Alice,
and certainly not from me.

1024
01:09:47,895 --> 01:09:50,455
I never took off my pants,
as you may or may not remember.

1025
01:09:50,664 --> 01:09:52,325
There are laws against
drugging people.

1026
01:09:52,533 --> 01:09:56,526
Oh, please. You took it voluntarily.
Nobody slipped it into your drink.

1027
01:09:58,105 --> 01:10:01,506
And you chased it with one of the most
expensive wines in the world.

1028
01:10:01,709 --> 01:10:05,110
You're just in a dither because you've
discovered you can swing both ways.

1029
01:10:07,414 --> 01:10:09,245
You see...

1030
01:10:10,317 --> 01:10:12,182
...I needed to get something on you.

1031
01:10:12,386 --> 01:10:15,651
Of course, your behavior with Lanny
might have been even better than this.

1032
01:10:15,856 --> 01:10:17,619
But I'd already set the wheels
in motion.

1033
01:10:17,825 --> 01:10:21,818
And as I was dying to see
you and Alice get it on...

1034
01:10:22,296 --> 01:10:24,423
Well, these are just a sample.

1035
01:10:32,039 --> 01:10:34,872
Why would she agree to do this?
Doesn't she want a career?

1036
01:10:35,075 --> 01:10:37,339
Well, it's your career
I'm worried about.

1037
01:10:37,912 --> 01:10:40,244
You're a journalist
playing loose with the rules.

1038
01:10:40,648 --> 01:10:43,173
She's just a vulnerable young singer
you seduced.

1039
01:10:43,384 --> 01:10:46,410
A promising... Oh, good heavens.

1040
01:10:46,787 --> 01:10:49,517
Promising artist
that I happen to manage.

1041
01:10:49,723 --> 01:10:51,520
You met her through me...

1042
01:10:51,725 --> 01:10:53,625
...and had your way with her.

1043
01:10:58,332 --> 01:10:59,959
What do you want from me?

1044
01:11:02,937 --> 01:11:05,269
You're going to continue
writing the book.

1045
01:11:05,472 --> 01:11:09,374
I'm going to continue telling you
juicy stories, funny stories...

1046
01:11:09,577 --> 01:11:11,670
...heart-tugging stories.

1047
01:11:11,912 --> 01:11:14,142
And you're not going to ask me
a single question...

1048
01:11:14,348 --> 01:11:16,578
...about what happened
to the girl in New Jersey.

1049
01:11:17,685 --> 01:11:20,711
You're going to go to your publisher,
say you tried every angle...

1050
01:11:20,921 --> 01:11:23,856
...but you could find nothing odd
or suspicious in what I told you.

1051
01:11:30,664 --> 01:11:33,565
I'll even try to spice it up a little,
talk about how...

1052
01:11:33,767 --> 01:11:36,736
...the night before the telethon,
I wanted to sleep like a babe...

1053
01:11:36,937 --> 01:11:39,201
...so to cover my bets,
I kept a few babes on hand.

1054
01:11:40,174 --> 01:11:41,732
Well, not exactly on my hand...

1055
01:11:41,942 --> 01:11:45,309
...and that's not my preference,
as you might have gathered by now.

1056
01:11:54,888 --> 01:11:58,790
So you get your bestseller,
I get my million.

1057
01:11:58,993 --> 01:12:00,255
Everyone goes home happy.

1058
01:12:00,461 --> 01:12:03,692
You've dreaded talking about
Maureen O'Flaherty since we met.

1059
01:12:03,897 --> 01:12:06,058
If it's something you're so
desperate to avoid...

1060
01:12:06,267 --> 01:12:08,258
...why would you ever agree
to do this book?

1061
01:12:08,969 --> 01:12:10,630
I need the money.

1062
01:12:10,838 --> 01:12:14,239
Vince, anything you say
in my presence is mine to use.

1063
01:12:15,242 --> 01:12:18,143
Everything you said last night
and everything you've just told me.

1064
01:12:18,345 --> 01:12:21,075
And since I'm also allowed to include
contextual background...

1065
01:12:21,282 --> 01:12:23,307
...I can write about
how you set me up...

1066
01:12:23,517 --> 01:12:26,884
...how you tried to blackmail me.
I'll even include those Polaroids.

1067
01:12:27,087 --> 01:12:30,420
It's your word against mine. We have
a contract. Everything's in my words.

1068
01:12:30,624 --> 01:12:33,923
We've agreed to your answers,
but there's nothing to stop me...

1069
01:12:34,128 --> 01:12:38,827
...from putting any information I want
into a question I ask.

1070
01:12:39,900 --> 01:12:42,869
Information that I'd like to be
public knowledge...

1071
01:12:43,804 --> 01:12:46,272
...or that the police
might wanna look into.

1072
01:12:50,911 --> 01:12:55,245
Would you like me to fire one of my
loaded questions, on the record?

1073
01:12:56,116 --> 01:12:57,879
Sure.

1074
01:13:04,958 --> 01:13:06,949
Vince...

1075
01:13:07,461 --> 01:13:10,897
...in your suite
at the Versailles Hotel in Miami...

1076
01:13:11,565 --> 01:13:13,931
...was it your or Lanny's idea...

1077
01:13:14,134 --> 01:13:17,467
...to put Maureen's body into the case
containing shellfish and ice...

1078
01:13:17,671 --> 01:13:19,332
...and have it shipped
to New Jersey?

1079
01:13:24,211 --> 01:13:27,078
No answer, Mr. Collins?
So noted.

1080
01:13:27,715 --> 01:13:30,582
Oh, and incidentally,
by not answering...

1081
01:13:30,784 --> 01:13:33,378
...you're in violation of your contract.

1082
01:13:33,988 --> 01:13:37,185
What a shame.
I understood you needed that money.

1083
01:13:51,905 --> 01:13:54,066
Oh, no. Oh, God.

1084
01:13:54,274 --> 01:13:57,971
Oh, God.
Oh, God. Oh, God!

1085
01:14:06,754 --> 01:14:08,517
Was that how
you murdered Maureen?

1086
01:14:21,969 --> 01:14:23,800
Ask Lanny.

1087
01:14:26,573 --> 01:14:28,598
He's the one who knows.

1088
01:14:47,094 --> 01:14:50,791
<i>It wasn't that hard for him
to get the suite he wanted.</i>

1089
01:14:50,998 --> 01:14:54,991
<i>The Versailles was still one of the
fanciest of the hotels along the beach.</i>

1090
01:14:55,202 --> 01:14:57,864
<i>But by then, its era had passed.</i>

1091
01:14:59,273 --> 01:15:00,865
Thank you, sir.

1092
01:15:10,317 --> 01:15:12,649
<i>All the furniture was new.</i>

1093
01:15:12,886 --> 01:15:15,218
<i>It had been 15 years...</i>

1094
01:15:15,923 --> 01:15:17,914
<i>... but the floor plan...</i>

1095
01:15:18,125 --> 01:15:20,286
<i>... was still the same.</i>

1096
01:15:21,095 --> 01:15:23,325
<i>In that spot...</i>

1097
01:15:23,664 --> 01:15:26,565
<i>... that was where the truth
had come out.</i>

1098
01:15:27,634 --> 01:15:30,398
<i>That was why she had to die.</i>

1099
01:15:41,248 --> 01:15:43,808
Are you Japanese or Chinese?

1100
01:15:45,052 --> 01:15:46,747
Vietnamese.

1101
01:15:47,221 --> 01:15:50,486
The kitchen tell me
you famous person.

1102
01:15:50,691 --> 01:15:52,625
Why you famous?

1103
01:15:52,993 --> 01:15:55,120
They didn't tell you my name?

1104
01:15:55,329 --> 01:15:56,523
No.

1105
01:15:56,730 --> 01:15:58,425
What is it?

1106
01:16:00,834 --> 01:16:02,563
Lanny Morris.

1107
01:16:03,303 --> 01:16:04,964
It's a Jewish name...

1108
01:16:05,172 --> 01:16:06,639
...but I'm a nebbish.

1109
01:16:07,908 --> 01:16:10,342
You ordered three bottle
of champagne.

1110
01:16:10,544 --> 01:16:11,806
You want me to open one now?

1111
01:16:12,513 --> 01:16:14,538
Or wait until friend come?

1112
01:16:15,649 --> 01:16:17,173
Open all three.

1113
01:16:18,819 --> 01:16:21,117
Are you really famous, Mr. Morris?

1114
01:16:22,356 --> 01:16:23,983
In my day.

1115
01:16:24,424 --> 01:16:26,483
Before your time, I suppose.

1116
01:16:27,494 --> 01:16:30,054
I come from the north of Vietnam.

1117
01:16:30,264 --> 01:16:32,596
In my town, there is no television.

1118
01:16:32,799 --> 01:16:37,099
<i>She explained that American movies
had been banned where she grew up.</i>

1119
01:16:42,342 --> 01:16:45,004
<i>She got better tips pretending
she was Madame Butterfly...</i>

1120
01:16:45,212 --> 01:16:48,272
<i>... than by telling people
where she was really from.</i>

1121
01:16:49,416 --> 01:16:51,509
What did you do, Mr. Morris?

1122
01:16:52,586 --> 01:16:55,111
I made Vince Collins' life...

1123
01:16:55,556 --> 01:16:57,649
...very difficult.

1124
01:16:57,858 --> 01:17:01,055
<i>She didn't understand, but her policy
was not to linger in the rooms...</i>

1125
01:17:01,261 --> 01:17:03,195
<i>... of solitary gentlemen.</i>

1126
01:17:04,598 --> 01:17:08,898
<i>He signed the room-service check
under Lanny's name.</i>

1127
01:17:11,138 --> 01:17:12,662
Thank you.

1128
01:17:35,729 --> 01:17:37,993
<i>There was no ice or water
left in the buckets...</i>

1129
01:17:38,198 --> 01:17:40,996
<i>... when his body was discovered
the next morning.</i>

1130
01:17:42,269 --> 01:17:46,000
<i>He had dumped the ice into
the bathtub and died in it.</i>

1131
01:17:47,240 --> 01:17:50,334
<i>He must have felt
there was some poetry in it.</i>

1132
01:17:53,747 --> 01:17:56,113
<i>His plan was to drink
enough champagne...</i>

1133
01:17:56,316 --> 01:17:57,715
<i>... with enough sleeping pills...</i>

1134
01:17:57,918 --> 01:18:01,820
<i>... so that ending things would
become an acceptable idea.</i>

1135
01:18:02,556 --> 01:18:04,456
<i>He could manage that.</i>

1136
01:18:05,258 --> 01:18:08,591
<i>He knew for certain
he couldn't manage anything else.</i>

1137
01:18:12,165 --> 01:18:13,723
Hi.

1138
01:18:16,003 --> 01:18:18,699
I thought you were
gonna be out all afternoon.

1139
01:18:23,443 --> 01:18:25,206
I'm sorry.

1140
01:18:25,646 --> 01:18:27,511
It's okay.

1141
01:18:28,482 --> 01:18:30,507
This was under the door.

1142
01:18:38,091 --> 01:18:39,353
What is it?

1143
01:18:40,994 --> 01:18:43,121
Chapter three.

1144
01:18:44,898 --> 01:18:49,198
<i>John, as my lawyer, I want you
to know that this next chapter...</i>

1145
01:18:49,403 --> 01:18:52,372
<i>... is to be read
after Vince and my death...</i>

1146
01:18:52,572 --> 01:18:57,236
<i>... and is only to be used under
the most extreme of circumstances.</i>

1147
01:18:58,945 --> 01:19:01,038
<i>We knew we wanted to make
an early night of it...</i>

1148
01:19:01,248 --> 01:19:04,684
<i>... with the telethon starting the next
day, so Vince suggested we dine in...</i>

1149
01:19:04,885 --> 01:19:07,877
<i>... so Maureen could do
the interview for her campus paper.</i>

1150
01:19:08,088 --> 01:19:13,082
This is a gift for us
from the audience...

1151
01:19:13,727 --> 01:19:17,663
...from the people,
the people that are out there.

1152
01:19:18,532 --> 01:19:22,764
Sooner or later you gotta say,
